body:
> Can you precise what you call "when doing a search on a subset..?"

I'm doing it with the three examples for which I specifically tagged you.
A screenshot wouldn't help.
In a shop, in the _Shoes_ page, you only want to list _Shoes_ results, not anything else. You hence don't want the user to be able to remove the _Shoes_ refinement.

``` js
var search = instantsearch(/* ... */);
// ...
search.addWidget({
  init: ({helper}) => { helper.toggleRefinement('category', 'Shoes') };
});
// Now, currentRefinedValues will list Shoes when we don't want it listed
// Now, a refinementList on category will list Shoes when we don't want it listed
// Now, if you click a clearAll widget, it will remove Shoes when we don't want it to be removed
```

> > add the generateSecuredAPIKey
> 
> Careful this is a node.js only method

Which is why I said "add".

---

Food for thought after thinking about this. The `securedAPIKey` only solves the `currentRefinedValues` and the `clearAll` issue. However, for `refinementList` the `Shoes` option will be listed, and can be toggled endlessly without changing anything. So in the end, this isn't a good solution.

Yeah! I'm late to the party, but this issue got me thinking. I've added an issue in the helper that could help us here https://github.com/algolia/algoliasearch-helper-js/issues/273 (tldr: it fixes a reset point to which all values would go back, if we "clear" them). If we add the capability to clearly express which field should not change, we could have a headless widget that does the constant configuration. The API would look like : 

``` js
var instantsearch = instantsearch();
instantsearch.addWidget(FixConfigWidget({
  constants: ['categories',  'tags']
}))
```

Do you think that could help here?
